Are there any plans, or is it even possible, to support NativeLibrary in dotnet standard?

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.runtime.interopservices.nativelibrary?view=netcore-3.1

I have a dotnet standard 2.1 library that needs to load a c++ library, but we want to support multiple versions of the library (linux and windows).

Example usage: 
```C#
static class NativeMethods
{
	private const string LibraryName = "something";
	static NativeMethods()
	{
		NativeLibrary.SetDllImportResolver(typeof(NativeMethods).Assembly, ImportResolver);
	}
	private static IntPtr ImportResolver(string libraryName, Assembly assembly, DllImportSearchPath? searchPath)
	{
		IntPtr libHandle = IntPtr.Zero;
		if (libraryName == NativeMethods.LibraryName)
		{
			string library;
			if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Linux))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.so";	
			} 
			else if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dylib";
			}
			else
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dll";
			}
			var libraryLoaded = NativeLibrary.TryLoad(library, assembly, DllImportSearchPath.AssemblyDirectory, out libHandle);
			if (!libraryLoaded)
			{
				throw new Exception($"Unable to Load Library: {library}");
			}
		}
		return libHandle;
	}
```

Alternatively, is there another way to load a cross platform C++ code in a dotnet standard?

There is currently no method to reliably get the arity, type parameters/arguments and original generic symbol of a symbol without explicitly checking for whether it's `INamedTypeSymbol` or `IMethodSymbol`. This defeats the purpose of the API; which should be properly abstracted.

In my case at least, where my analyzer is about generic types and methods, I've had to make extensions to provide that capability.

# Proposed API

New interface:
```csharp
interface IGenericSymbol : ISymbol
{
    bool IsGeneric { get; }
    int Arity { get; }
    ImmutableArray<ITypeParameterSymbol> TypeParameters { get; }
    ImmutableArray<ITypeSymbol> TypeArguments { get; }
    IGenericSymbol ConstructedFrom { get; }
}
```

Changes to existing APIs:
```csharp
interface INamedTypeSymbol : IGenericSymbol, ITypeSymbol
{
    // Everything else remains the same
}
```
```csharp
interface IMethodSymbol : IGenericSymbol
{
    // Everything else remains the same
}
```

Likewise this could offer the ability to add a `DeclaringSymbol` property in `ITypeParameterSymbol` that returns a `IGenericSymbol`. The API would look like this:

```csharp
interface ITypeParameterSymbol : // ...
{
    IGenericSymbol DeclaringSymbol { get; }
    // Everything else remains the same
}
```

Note: the `DeclaringSymbol` could also be named `DeclaringGenericSymbol`.

